Part 3

The lawyer's name was Bannerjee.

He had a small office in Dalhousie Square that smelled of red tape and damp sheepskin folders.

He arrived at Bagbazar on a Saturday morning, his black leather briefcase bulging with three copies of the transfer deed.

"This is the second time, Vikram babu," Bannerjee said, setting the papers on the register table.

Ananya was standing near the well, holding a broom.

She had stopped sweeping.

She was looking at the white paper documents, her eyes moving from the lawyer's clean cuffs to Vikram's hand.

"The second time is easier," Vikram said.

"It is never easier," Bannerjee said. "The first time, it was family. Your brother. This time, it is an employee. A boy who has been here four years. The board will ask questions. The international donors will want to know why the founder is walking away."

"The founder is tired," Vikram said.

He signed.

His signature didn't have the sharp 'A' it had in Odisha.

It was looser. The ink from the ballpoint pen had run slightly at the edge of the 'V', leaving a small blue blur on the bond paper.

Ramu's nephew brought the tea.

Mismatched glasses.

Red tea, but today the palm sugar was missing. It was just ginger and water.

Bannerjee drank his quickly, packed the signed deeds into his leather bag, and stood up.

"Rehman has the power now," the lawyer said. "The banking, the Barasat unit, the international funds. He is the CEO."

"Good," Vikram said.

---

Vikram fell sick three days later.

It was the winter cough, the cold from the Hooghly river settling in his chest, making every breath sound like the dry regulator hiss.

He stayed on his wooden bench in the side room.

Sarita brought him hot barley water twice a day.

"Rehman hasn't come," she said on the fourth morning.

"He is busy with the Barasat audit," Vikram said.

"He is in Alipore, Vikram. The supervisor said the silver sedan was parked outside the office for three hours yesterday. He didn't come up."

"Let him be," Vikram said. "The new shoes take time to fit."

The phone near the register table rang at seven that evening.

Vikram was alone in the room.

He walked out, his legs slightly stiff from the fever, and picked up the receiver.

"Uncle."

It was Rehman's voice.

It was quiet. The thick, drunk anger of the terrace had gone, replaced by a dry, hollow rattle.

"Rehman," Vikram said. "Where are you?"

"I am in Alipore."

"Come to Bagbazar. The lawyer has sent the deeds."

A long silence down the line.

The sound of city traffic, distant and light, came through the receiver.

"I can't," the boy said.

"Why?"

"I looked at the signature on the copy," Rehman said. "The blue blur at the end. You didn't even read the clauses."

"The clauses don't change the decision, Rehman."

"I am ashamed, uncle," the boy whispered. "I said those things on the terrace. The candle. The sun. It was the whiskey."

"It is alright."

"It is not," Rehman said. "I can't look at your face. I will handle the Barasat work from Alipore. Don't call me."

The line went dead.

Vikram held the receiver for a minute, the dial tone humming its dry, mechanical drone.

---

Rehman didn't call the next week.

Or the week after.

By the end of December, the Barasat manager called Bagbazar.

"Vikram babu," the manager said. "The salary release is pending. Rehman sir hasn't signed the bank authorization."

"Is he not in Alipore?"

"The house is locked, sir. The security guard said he left with two bags on Tuesday. He took a cab to the station."

Vikram took his bag.

He went to Alipore himself.

The apartment building was tall, the concrete walls painted cream, with large glass balconies reflecting the winter sun.

The security guard, an old Gorkha named Thapa, was sitting on a plastic chair near the gate.

He recognized Vikram from the newspaper photos.

"Rehman saab left," Thapa said.

"When?"

"Tuesday night, sir. He had two blue bags. The ones with the rusted zips."

"Did he leave an address?"

"No, sir. He just said he was going to Cuttack. He looked sick. His eyes were very dry, like he hadn't slept for weeks."

Vikram stood near the gate.

A silver sedan, identical to the one Rehman had driven, was parked near the wall.

It was covered in a thick layer of grey city dust, someone having traced a name into the dirt of the rear window with a finger.

*Ummed.*

He looked at the dusty window.

The Alipore house was locked.

The silver sedan was empty.

And Rehman was gone.

[End of Part 3]
